Linux Basic Commands with Description:

Mastering basic Linux commands is essential for efficient system administration. Here's a comprehensive list of basic Linux commands:
date: Display the current date and time.
cal: Display a calendar.
ls: List directory contents.
ls -l: List directory contents in long format.
ls -a: List directory contents including hidden files.
ls -al: List directory contents in long format including hidden files.
mkdir: Create a new directory.
pwd: Print the current working directory.
touch: Create an empty file or update file timestamps.
clear: Clear the terminal screen.
cd: Change directory.
cd ..: Move to the parent directory.
rm: Remove files or directories.
cat: Concatenate and display file content.
echo: Display a line of text/string.
zcat: Display compressed file content.
head: Output the first part of files.
tail: Output the last part of files.
less: Display file contents one screen at a time.
more: Display file contents one screen at a time (backward compatible).
cp: Copy files or directories.
mv: Move or rename files or directories.
diff: Compare files line by line.
vi: Text editor (terminal-based).
vim: Improved version of vi.
nano: Simple text editor.
df -h: Display disk usage in human-readable format.
top: Display Linux processes.
ps: Display information about processes.
kill: Terminate processes.
free: Display memory usage.
vmstat: Display virtual memory statistics.
htop: Interactive process viewer.
iftop: Display bandwidth usage on an interface.
atop: Advanced interactive system monitor.
netstat: Display network connections.
nslookup: Query Internet name servers interactively.
dig: DNS lookup utility.
ip a: Show information for all network interfaces.
ping: Send ICMP echo request to network hosts.
ifconfig: Configure network interfaces.
mtr: Network diagnostic tool.
hostname: Print or set system hostname.
whois: Lookup domain registration information.
wget: Download files from the web.
watch: Execute a program periodically.
nmap: Network exploration and security auditing tool.
which: Locate a command.
man: Display manual pages.
uname: Print system information.
uptime: Display system uptime.
who: Display who is logged in.
whoami: Print effective username.
id: Print user and group information.
sudo -i: Execute a command as another user.
apt-get: Package manager for Debian-based systems.
yum: Package manager for Red Hat-based systems.
grep: Search text patterns.
find: Search files and directories.
zip: Package and compress files.
unzip: Unzip compressed files.
alias: Create aliases for commands.
history: Display command history.
exit: Exit the shell.
These commands form the backbone of Linux administration and are crucial for managing and maintaining Linux systems effectively.
